Lemma 21.4 In an arbitrary triangle we have
$$
a b+b c+c a=r^{2}+s^{2}+4 r R \quad \text { and } \quad a^{2}+b^{2}+c^{2}=2\left(s^{2}-4 R r-r^{2}\right)
$$

Proof We have
$$
\begin{aligned}
r^{2}+s^{2}+4 r R & =\frac{P^{2}}{s^{2}}+s^{2}+\frac{a b c}{P} \cdot \frac{P}{s}=\frac{(s-a)(s-b)(s-c)}{s}+s^{2}+\frac{a b c}{s} \\
& =\frac{s^{3}-a s^{2}-b s^{2}-c s^{2}+a b s+b c s+c a s-a b c+s^{3}+a b c}{s} \\
& =2 s^{2}-s(a+b+c)+a b+b c+c a \\
& =2 s^{2}-2 s^{2}+a b+b c+c a=a b+b c+c a
\end{aligned}
$$

Hence
$$
\begin{equation*}
a b+b c+c a=r^{2}+s^{2}+4 r R \tag{1}
\end{equation*}
$$

Now by (1) we have
$$
\begin{aligned}
a b+b c+c a & =r^{2}+s^{2}+4 r R=\frac{1}{2}\left(2 r^{2}+8 r R+\frac{(a+b+c)^{2}}{2}\right) \\
& =\frac{1}{2}\left(2 r^{2}+8 r R+\frac{a^{2}+b^{2}+c^{2}}{2}\right)+\frac{a b+b c+c a}{2}
\end{aligned}
$$
from which it follows that
$$
\begin{equation*}
a b+b c+c a=2 r^{2}+8 r R+\frac{a^{2}+b^{2}+c^{2}}{2} \tag{2}
\end{equation*}
$$

Now (1) and (2) yields
$$
\begin{equation*}
a^{2}+b^{2}+c^{2}=2\left(s^{2}-4 R r-r^{2}\right) \tag{3}
\end{equation*}
$$

Without proof we will give the following lemma.

In an arbitrary triangle we have
$$
\begin{equation*}
s^{2} \leq 4 R^{2}+4 R r+3 r^{2} \tag{4}
\end{equation*}
$$

In an arbitrary triangle we have $a^{2}+b^{2}+c^{2} \leq 8 R^{2}+4 r^{2}$.
Proof From (3) and (4) we have
$$
a^{2}+b^{2}+c^{2}=2\left(s^{2}-4 R r-r^{2}\right) \leq 2\left(4 R^{2}+4 R r+3 r^{2}-4 R r-r^{2}\right)=8 R^{2}+4 r^{2}
$$

Hence
$$
