We have that 
$$
\frac{p^{2}+q}{p q-r}-\frac{1}{p} \geq 2
$$
i.e.
$$
\frac{p^{2}+1}{p-r}-\frac{1}{p} \geq 2
$$
which is equivalent as follows
$$
\begin{align*}
p^{3} & +p-p+r \geq 2 p^{2}-2 p r \\
& \Leftrightarrow \quad p^{3}-2 p^{2}+2 p r+r \geq 0 \\
& \Leftrightarrow \quad p^{3}-2 p^{2}+r(2 p+1) \geq 0 \tag{2}
\end{align*}
$$

Let
$$
\begin{equation*}
f(p)=p^{3}-2 p^{2}+r(2 p+1) \tag{3}
\end{equation*}
$$

From $p^{2} \geq 3 q=3$  it follows that $p \geq \sqrt{3}$.
If $p \geq 2$ then clearly $f(p) \geq 0$.
Let $\sqrt{3} \leq p<2$.
By $N_{1}: p^{3}-4 p q+9 r \geq 0$ we have
$$
\begin{equation*}
p^{3}-4 p+9 r \geq 0, \quad \text { i.e. } \quad r \geq \frac{4 p-p^{3}}{9} \tag{4}
\end{equation*}
$$

By (3) and (4) we obtain
$$
\begin{aligned}
f(p) & =p^{3}-2 p^{2}+r(2 p+1) \geq p^{3}-2 p^{2}+\left(\frac{4 p-p^{3}}{9}\right)(2 p+1) \\
& =-2 p(p-2)(p-1)^{2} \geq 0
\end{aligned}
$$

The last inequality holds, since $p<2$. So we have proved (2), and we are done.

We'll homogenize as follows
$$
\begin{aligned}
\frac{x^{5}-x^{2}}{x^{5}+y^{2}+z^{2}} & \geq \frac{x^{5}-x^{2} \cdot x y z}{x^{5}+x y z\left(y^{2}+z^{2}\right)}=\frac{x^{4}-x^{2} y z}{x^{4}+y z\left(y^{2}+z^{2}\right)} \\
& \geq \frac{x^{4}-x^{2}\left(\frac{y^{2}+z^{2}}{2}\right)}{x^{4}+\left(\frac{y^{2}+z^{2}}{2}\right)\left(y^{2}+z^{2}\right)}=\frac{2 x^{4}-x^{2}\left(y^{2}+z^{2}\right)}{2 x^{4}+\left(y^{2}+z^{2}\right)^{2}}
\end{aligned}
$$

Similarly we get
$$
\frac{y^{5}-y^{2}}{y^{5}+z^{2}+x^{2}} \geq \frac{2 y^{4}-y^{2}\left(z^{2}+x^{2}\right)}{2 y^{4}+\left(z^{2}+x^{2}\right)^{2}} \quad \text { and } \quad \frac{z^{5}-z^{2}}{z^{5}+x^{2}+y^{2}} \geq \frac{2 z^{4}-z^{2}\left(x^{2}+y^{2}\right)}{2 z^{4}+\left(x^{2}+y^{2}\right)^{2}}
$$

So it suffices to show that
$$
\begin{equation*}
\frac{2 x^{4}-x^{2}\left(y^{2}+z^{2}\right)}{2 x^{4}+\left(y^{2}+z^{2}\right)^{2}}+\frac{2 y^{4}-y^{2}\left(z^{2}+x^{2}\right)}{2 y^{4}+\left(z^{2}+x^{2}\right)^{2}}+\frac{2 z^{4}-z^{2}\left(x^{2}+y^{2}\right)}{2 z^{4}+\left(x^{2}+y^{2}\right)^{2}} \geq 0 \tag{1}
\end{equation*}
$$

Let $x^{2}=a, y^{2}=b, z^{2}=c$. Then inequality (1) becomes
$$
\begin{equation*}
\frac{2 a^{2}-a(b+c)}{2 a^{2}+(b+c)^{2}}+\frac{2 b^{2}-b(c+a)}{2 b^{2}+(c+a)^{2}}+\frac{2 c^{2}-c(a+b)}{2 c^{2}+(a+b)^{2}} \geq 0 \tag{2}
\end{equation*}
$$

After some algebraic operations we can rewrite inequality (2) as follows
$$
\begin{aligned}
& (b-c)^{2} \frac{a^{2}+a(b+c)+b^{2}-b c+c^{2}}{\left(2 b^{2}+(c+a)^{2}\right)\left(2 c^{2}+(a+b)^{2}\right)} \\
& \quad+(c-a)^{2} \frac{b^{2}+b(a+c)+c^{2}-c a+a^{2}}{\left(2 a^{2}+(b+c)^{2}\right)\left(2 c^{2}+(a+b)^{2}\right)} \\
& \quad+(a-b)^{2} \frac{c^{2}+c(a+b)+a^{2}-a b+b^{2}}{\left(2 a^{2}+(b+c)^{2}\right)\left(2 b^{2}+(c+a)^{2}\right)} \geq 0
\end{aligned}
$$
which is true due to the obvious inequality: if $x, y \in \mathbb{R}$ then $x^{2}-x y+y^{2} \geq 0$.

