By (1) and (2) we obtain
$$
s \geq 3 \sqrt[3]{s r^{2}}, \quad \text { i.e. } \quad s \geq 3 \sqrt{3} r
$$

Equality occurs if and only if $a=b=c$.

By the power mean inequality we have that
$$
\begin{aligned}
& M_{2}(a, b, c) \leq M_{3}(a, b, c) \\
& \quad \Leftrightarrow \quad \sqrt{\frac{a^{2}+b^{2}+c^{2}}{3}} \leq \sqrt[3]{\frac{a^{3}+b^{3}+c^{3}}{3}} \\
& \quad \Leftrightarrow \quad\left(a^{2}+b^{2}+c^{2}\right)^{3} \leq 3\left(a^{3}+b^{3}+c^{3}\right)^{2}
\end{aligned}
$$

For any real number $x$, the numbers $x-1, x^{2}-1, x^{3}-1$ and $x^{4}-1$, are of the same sign.

Therefore
$$
(x-1)\left(x^{3}-1\right) \geq 0, \quad\left(x^{2}-1\right)\left(x^{3}-1\right) \geq 0 \quad \text { and } \quad\left(x^{3}-1\right)\left(x^{4}-1\right) \geq 0
$$
i.e.
$$
\begin{array}{r}
c^{4}-c^{3}-c+1 \geq 0 \tag{1}
\end{array}
$$
$$
\begin{array}{r}
b^{5}-b^{3}-b^{2}+1 \geq 0 \tag{2}
\end{array}
$$
$$
\begin{array}{r}
a^{7}-a^{4}-a^{3}+1 \geq 0 \tag{3}
\end{array}
$$

By (1), (2) and (3) we have
$$
a^{7}-a^{4}+3 \geq a^{3}+2, \quad b^{5}-b^{2}+3 \geq b^{3}+2 \quad \text { and } \quad c^{4}-c+3 \geq c^{3}+2
$$

After multiplying these inequalities it follows that
$$
\begin{equation*}
\left(a^{7}-a^{4}+3\right)\left(b^{5}-b^{2}+3\right)\left(c^{4}-c+3\right) \geq\left(a^{3}+2\right)\left(b^{3}+2\right)\left(c^{3}+2\right) \tag{4}
\end{equation*}
$$

Analogously as in Problem 126, we can prove that
$$
\begin{equation*}
\left(a^{3}+2\right)\left(b^{3}+2\right)\left(c^{3}+2\right) \geq(a+b+c)^{3} \tag{5}
\end{equation*}
$$

By the obvious inequality $(a+b+c)^{2} \geq 3(a b+b c+c a)$, since $a b+b c+c a=3$ we deduce that
$$
\begin{equation*}
a+b+c \geq 3 \tag{6}
\end{equation*}
$$

Finally from (4), (5) and (6) we obtain the required inequality.
Equality occurs iff $a=b=c=1$.

