& \Leftrightarrow \frac{1}{(2 \sqrt{a b})^{2}}+\frac{1}{(2 \sqrt{b c})^{2}}+\frac{1}{(2 \sqrt{c a})^{2}}+\frac{2}{(2 \sqrt{a b})(2 \sqrt{b c})(2 \sqrt{c a})}=1
\end{aligned}
$$

We can make the substitutions
$$
\begin{equation*}
\frac{1}{2 \sqrt{b c}}=\sin \frac{\alpha}{2}, \quad \frac{1}{2 \sqrt{c a}}=\sin \frac{\beta}{2}, \quad \frac{1}{2 \sqrt{a b}}=\sin \frac{\gamma}{2} \tag{1}
\end{equation*}
$$
where $\alpha, \beta, \gamma \in(0, \pi)$ and $\alpha+\beta+\gamma=\pi$.
From (1) we easily obtain
$$
\begin{equation*}
\frac{1}{a}=\frac{2 \sin \frac{\beta}{2} \sin \frac{\gamma}{2}}{\sin \frac{\alpha}{2}}, \quad \frac{1}{b}=\frac{2 \sin \frac{\gamma}{2} \sin \frac{\alpha}{2}}{\sin \frac{\beta}{2}} \quad \text { and } \quad \frac{1}{c}=\frac{2 \sin \frac{\alpha}{2} \sin \frac{\beta}{2}}{\sin \frac{\gamma}{2}} \tag{2}
\end{equation*}
$$

Now the given inequality becomes
$$
2\sin \frac{\alpha}{2}+2 \sin \frac{\beta}{2}+2 \sin \frac{\gamma}{2} \leq 3
$$
i.e.
$$
\sin \frac{\alpha}{2}+\sin \frac{\beta}{2}+\sin \frac{\gamma}{2} \leq \frac{3}{2}
$$
where $\alpha, \beta, \gamma \in(0, \pi)$ and $\alpha+\beta+\gamma=\pi$, which clearly holds due to $N_{3}$.
We need to show the left inequality which, due to (2) is equivalent to
$$
\begin{equation*}
\frac{2 \sin \frac{\beta}{2} \sin \frac{\gamma}{2}}{\sin \frac{\alpha}{2}}+\frac{2 \sin \frac{\gamma}{2} \sin \frac{\alpha}{2}}{\sin \frac{\beta}{2}}+\frac{2 \sin \frac{\alpha}{2} \sin \frac{\beta}{2}}{\sin \frac{\gamma}{2}} \geq 3 \tag{3}
\end{equation*}
$$

Let $a, b, c$ be the lengths of the sides of the triangle with angles $\alpha, \beta$ and $\gamma$, let $s$ be its semi-perimeter, and let $x=s-a, y=s-b, z=s-c$.

Then inequality (3) is equivalent to
$$
\frac{x}{y+z}+\frac{y}{z+x}+\frac{z}{x+y} \geq \frac{3}{2}
$$
i.e. we obtain the famous Nesbitt's inequality, which clearly holds. And we are done.

