Applying Chebishev's inequality we get
$\left(x_{1}+x_{2}+\cdots+x_{n}\right)\left(\ln x_{1}+\ln x_{2}+\cdots+\ln x_{n}\right) \leq n\left(x_{1} \ln x_{1}+x_{2} \ln x_{2}+\cdots+x_{n} \ln x_{n}\right)$, i.e.
$x_{1} \ln x_{1}+x_{2} \ln x_{2}+\cdots+x_{n} \ln x_{n} \geq \frac{x_{1}+x_{2}+\cdots+x_{n}}{n}\left(\ln x_{1}+\ln x_{2}+\cdots+\ln x_{n}\right)$.

We have
$$
\begin{aligned}
& \left(a+\frac{1}{b}\right)^{2}+\left(b+\frac{1}{c}\right)^{2}+\left(c+\frac{1}{a}\right)^{2} \\
& \quad=a^{2}+b^{2}+c^{2}+\frac{1}{a^{2}}+\frac{1}{b^{2}}+\frac{1}{c^{2}}+2\left(\frac{a}{b}+\frac{b}{c}+\frac{c}{a}\right) \\
& \quad=a^{2}+\frac{1}{a^{2}}+b^{2}+\frac{1}{b^{2}}+c^{2}+\frac{1}{c^{2}}+2\left(\frac{a}{b}+\frac{b}{c}+\frac{c}{a}\right)
\end{aligned}
$$
$$
\begin{aligned}
= & a^{2}+\frac{a b+b c+c a}{a^{2}}+b^{2}+\frac{a b+b c+c a}{b^{2}}+c^{2}+\frac{a b+b c+c a}{c^{2}} \\
& +2\left(\frac{a}{b}+\frac{b}{c}+\frac{c}{a}\right) \\
= & \left(a^{2}+b^{2}+c^{2}\right)+\left(\frac{b}{a}+\frac{c}{b}+\frac{a}{c}\right)+3\left(\frac{c}{a}+\frac{a}{b}+\frac{b}{c}\right)+\left(\frac{b c}{a^{2}}+\frac{c a}{b^{2}}+\frac{a b}{c^{2}}\right) \\
\geq & a b+b c+c a+3+9+3=1+3+9+3=16
\end{aligned}
$$

Clearly, equality occurs iff $a=b=c=1 / \sqrt{3}$.,By $Q M \geq A M$ we have
$$
\begin{equation*}
\left(a+\frac{1}{b}\right)^{2}+\left(b+\frac{1}{c}\right)^{2}+\left(c+\frac{1}{a}\right)^{2} \geq \frac{\left(a+b+c+\frac{1}{a}+\frac{1}{b}+\frac{1}{c}\right)^{2}}{3} \tag{1}
\end{equation*}
$$

By well-known $(a+b+c)^{2} \geq 3(a b+b c+c a)$ and $a b+b c+c a=1$ we obtain
$$
\begin{equation*}
a+b+c \geq \sqrt{3} \tag{2}
\end{equation*}
$$

According to $A M \geq G M$ we have
$$
1=a b+b c+c a \geq 3 \sqrt[3]{(a b c)^{2}}
$$
i.e.
$$
\frac{1}{\sqrt[3]{a b c}} \geq \sqrt{3}
$$

By $A M \geq G M$ and previous inequality we have
$$
\begin{equation*}
\frac{1}{a}+\frac{1}{b}+\frac{1}{c} \geq \frac{3}{\sqrt[3]{a b c}} \geq 3 \sqrt{3} \tag{3}
\end{equation*}
$$

Finally by (1), (2) and (3) we get
$$
\left(a+\frac{1}{b}\right)^{2}+\left(b+\frac{1}{c}\right)^{2}+\left(c+\frac{1}{a}\right)^{2} \geq \frac{(\sqrt{3}+3 \sqrt{3})^{2}}{3}=16
$$
as required. Equality occurs iff $a=b=c=1 / \sqrt{3}$.,By well-known inequality $x^{2}+y^{2}+z^{2} \geq x y+y z+z x$ we have
$$
\begin{aligned}
\left(a+\frac{1}{b}\right)^{2}+\left(b+\frac{1}{c}\right)^{2}+\left(c+\frac{1}{a}\right)^{2} \geq & \left(a+\frac{1}{b}\right)\left(b+\frac{1}{c}\right)+\left(b+\frac{1}{c}\right)\left(c+\frac{1}{a}\right) \\
& +\left(c+\frac{1}{a}\right)\left(a+\frac{1}{b}\right)
\end{aligned}
$$
i.e.
$$
\begin{align*}
\left(a+\frac{1}{b}\right)^{2}+\left(b+\frac{1}{c}\right)^{2}+\left(c+\frac{1}{a}\right)^{2} \geq & a b+b c+c a+\frac{a}{c}+\frac{b}{a}+\frac{c}{b}+3 \\
& +\frac{1}{a b}+\frac{1}{b c}+\frac{1}{c a} \tag{1}
\end{align*}
$$

Using $A M \geq G M$ and $A M \geq H M$ we get $\frac{a}{c}+\frac{b}{a}+\frac{c}{b} \geq 3 \sqrt[3]{\frac{a}{c} \cdot \frac{b}{a} \cdot \frac{c}{b}}=3$ and $\frac{1}{a b}+$ $\frac{1}{b c}+\frac{1}{c a} \geq \frac{9}{a b+b c+c a}=\frac{9}{1}=9$, respectively.

By last two inequalities and (1) we obtain
$$
\left(a+\frac{1}{b}\right)^{2}+\left(b+\frac{1}{c}\right)^{2}+\left(c+\frac{1}{a}\right)^{2} \geq 1+3+3+9=16
$$
as required.

We'll use the fact that the function $f(x)=x^{n}$ is concave on $(0, \infty)$.

So according to Jensen's inequality we have
$$
\frac{x^{n}+y^{n}}{2} \geq\left(\frac{x+y}{2}\right)^{n}
$$

Remark Note that this is a power mean inequality.
Now we have
$$
\begin{equation*}
\frac{1}{2}\left(\left(1+\frac{a}{b}\right)^{n}+\left(1+\frac{b}{a}\right)^{n}\right) \geq\left(\frac{1+a / b+1+b / a}{2}\right)^{n}=\left(\frac{2+a / b+b / a}{2}\right)^{n} \tag{1}
\end{equation*}
$$

Using $\frac{a}{b}+\frac{b}{a} \geq 2$ and (1) we deduce
$$
\left(1+\frac{a}{b}\right)^{n}+\left(1+\frac{b}{a}\right)^{n} \geq 2\left(\frac{2+2}{2}\right)^{n}=2^{n+1}
$$

Theorem 40.Theorem:
Let $f:(a, b) \rightarrow \mathbb{R}$ be a convex function on the interval $(a, b)$. Let $n \in \mathbb{N}$ and $\alpha_{1}, \alpha_{2}, \ldots, \alpha_{n} \in(0,1)$ be real numbers such that $\alpha_{1}+\alpha_{2}+\cdots+\alpha_{n}=1$. Then for any $x_{1}, x_{2}, \ldots, x_{n} \in(a, b)$ we have
$$
f\left(\sum_{i=1}^{n} \alpha_{i} x_{i}\right) \leq \sum_{i=1}^{n} \alpha_{i} f\left(x_{i}\right)
$$
i.e.
$$
\begin{equation*}
f\left(\alpha_{1} x_{1}+\alpha_{2} x_{2}+\cdots+\alpha_{n} x_{n}\right) \leq \alpha_{1} f\left(x_{1}\right)+\alpha_{2} f\left(x_{2}\right)+\cdots+\alpha_{n} f\left(x_{n}\right) \tag{7.2}
\end{equation*}
$$

solution:
Applying the Cauchy-Schwarz inequality we have
$$
\begin{aligned}
& \frac{a}{b+c}+\frac{b}{c+d}+\frac{c}{d+e}+\frac{d}{e+a}+\frac{e}{a+b} \\
& \quad=\frac{a^{2}}{a b+a c}+\frac{b^{2}}{b c+b d}+\frac{c^{2}}{c d+c e}+\frac{d^{2}}{d e+a d}+\frac{e^{2}}{a e+b e} \\
& \quad \geq \frac{(a+b+c+d+e)^{2}}{a b+a c+a d+a e+b c+b d+b e+c d+c e+d e}
\end{aligned}
$$

So it is suffices to show that
$$
\frac{(a+b+c+d+e)^{2}}{a b+a c+a d+a e+b c+b d+b e+c d+c e+d e} \geq \frac{5}{2}
$$
which clearly holds.

Let $p=a+b+c, q=a b+b c+c a, r=a b c$.
From $\frac{1}{a+1}+\frac{1}{b+1}+\frac{1}{c+1}=2$ we deduce
$$
\begin{equation*}
(a+1)(b+1)+(b+1)(c+1)+(c+1)(a+1)=2(a+1)(b+1)(c+1) \tag{1}
\end{equation*}
$$

(1) is equivalent to
$$
3+2 p+q=2(1+p+q+r)
$$
i.e.
$$
\begin{equation*}
q+2 r=1 \tag{2}
\end{equation*}
$$
We easily get that
$$
\begin{aligned}
& \left(8 a^{2}+1\right)\left(8 b^{2}+1\right)+\left(8 b^{2}+1\right)\left(8 c^{2}+1\right)+\left(8 c^{2}+1\right)\left(8 a^{2}+1\right) \\
& \quad=64\left(q^{2}-2 p r\right)+16\left(p^{2}-2 q\right)+3
\end{aligned}
$$
and
$$
\left(8 a^{2}+1\right)\left(8 b^{2}+1\right)\left(8 c^{2}+1\right)=512 r^{2}+64\left(q^{2}-2 p r\right)+8\left(p^{2}-2 q\right)+1
$$

So inequality becomes
$$
64\left(q^{2}-2 p r\right)+16\left(p^{2}-2 q\right)+3 \geq 512 r^{2}+64\left(q^{2}-2 p r\right)+8\left(p^{2}-2 q\right)+1
$$
i.e.
$$
\begin{equation*}
8\left(p^{2}-2 q\right)+2 \geq 512 r^{2} \tag{3}
\end{equation*}
$$

Using that $q^{3} \geq 27 r^{2}$ and $q=1-2 r$ we get
$$
\begin{aligned}
& (1-2 r)^{3} \geq 27 r^{2} \quad \Leftrightarrow \quad 8 r^{3}+15 r^{2}+6 r-1 \leq 0 \\
& \quad \Leftrightarrow \quad(8 r-1)\left(r^{2}+2 r+1\right) \leq 0
\end{aligned}
$$
from where we deduce that
$$
\begin{equation*}
8 r-1 \leq 0, \quad \text { i.e. } \quad r \leq \frac{1}{8} \tag{4}
\end{equation*}
$$

Since $A M \geq H M$ we have
$$
((a+1)+(b+1)+(c+1))\left(\frac{1}{a+1}+\frac{1}{b+1}+\frac{1}{c+1}\right) \geq 9
$$
or
$$
2(a+b+c+3) \geq 9
$$
i.e.
$$
\begin{equation*}
p=a+b+c \geq \frac{3}{2} \tag{5}
\end{equation*}
$$

From  $p^{2} \geq 3 q$ it follows that
$$
\begin{equation*}
\frac{p^{2}}{3} \geq q \tag{6}
\end{equation*}
$$

By (5) and (6) we have
$$
\begin{equation*}
8\left(p^{2}-2 q\right)+2 \geq 8\left(p^{2}-2 \frac{p^{2}}{3}\right)+2=\frac{8}{3} p^{2}+2 \geq \frac{8}{3} \frac{9}{4}+2=8 \tag{7}
\end{equation*}
$$

From (3) and (7) we have that it suffices to show that
$$
8 \geq 512 r^{2}
$$
or
$$
r \leq \frac{1}{8}
$$
which is true according to (4). And we are done.

Theorem 40.Theorem:
Let $f:(a, b) \rightarrow \mathbb{R}$ be a convex function on the interval $(a, b)$. Let $n \in \mathbb{N}$ and $\alpha_{1}, \alpha_{2}, \ldots, \alpha_{n} \in(0,1)$ be real numbers such that $\alpha_{1}+\alpha_{2}+\cdots+\alpha_{n}=1$. Then for any $x_{1}, x_{2}, \ldots, x_{n} \in(a, b)$ we have
$$
f\left(\sum_{i=1}^{n} \alpha_{i} x_{i}\right) \leq \sum_{i=1}^{n} \alpha_{i} f\left(x_{i}\right)
$$
i.e.
$$
\begin{equation*}
f\left(\alpha_{1} x_{1}+\alpha_{2} x_{2}+\cdots+\alpha_{n} x_{n}\right) \leq \alpha_{1} f\left(x_{1}\right)+\alpha_{2} f\left(x_{2}\right)+\cdots+\alpha_{n} f\left(x_{n}\right) \tag{7.2}
\end{equation*}
$$

solution:
The following observation is crucial

$$
\begin{aligned}
(1+a b c)\left(\frac{1}{a(1+b)}+\frac{1}{b(1+c)}+\frac{1}{c(1+a)}\right)+3 & =\sum \frac{1+a b c+a+a b}{a(1+b)}= \\
& =\sum \frac{1+a}{a(1+b)}+\sum \frac{b(c+1)}{1+b}
\end{aligned}
$$

We use now twice the AM-GM Inequality to find that

$$
\sum \frac{1+a}{a(1+b)}+\sum \frac{b(c+1)}{1+b} \geq \frac{3}{\sqrt[3]{a b c}}+3 \sqrt[3]{a b c}
$$

And so we are left with the inequality

$$
\frac{\frac{3}{\sqrt[3]{a b c}}+3 \sqrt[3]{a b c}-3}{1+a b c} \geq \frac{3}{\sqrt[3]{a b c}(1+\sqrt[3]{a b c})}
$$

which is in fact an identity!

We have the inequalities

$$
\begin{gathered}
\sqrt{a^{2}+(1-b)^{2}}+\sqrt{b^{2}+(1-c)^{2}}+\sqrt{c^{2}+(1-a)^{2}} \geq \\
\quad \geq \frac{|a|+|1-b|}{\sqrt{2}}+\frac{|b|+|1-c|}{\sqrt{2}}+\frac{|c|+|1-a|}{\sqrt{2}}
\end{gathered}
$$

and because $|x|+|1-x| \geq 1$ for all real numbers $x$ the last quantity is at least $\frac{3 \sqrt{2}}{2}$.

We'll use the following well known inequalities:
For any $a, b, c>0$ we have $\frac{a}{b+c}+\frac{b}{c+a}+\frac{c}{a+b} \geq \frac{3}{2}$ (Nesbit's) and for any $x, y, z \geq$ 0 we have
$$
x^{2}+y^{2}+z^{2} \geq \frac{(x+y+z)^{2}}{3}
$$

Now we obtain
$$
\begin{aligned}
\frac{a}{(b+c)^{2}}+\frac{b}{(c+a)^{2}}+\frac{c}{(a+b)^{2}}= & \frac{a(a+b+c)}{(b+c)^{2}}+\frac{b(a+b+c)}{(c+a)^{2}}+\frac{c(a+b+c)}{(a+b)^{2}} \\
= & \left(\frac{a}{b+c}\right)^{2}+\left(\frac{b}{c+a}\right)^{2}+\left(\frac{c}{a+b}\right)^{2}+\frac{a}{b+c} \\
& +\frac{b}{c+a}+\frac{c}{a+b}
\end{aligned}
$$

Using previous well-known inequalities we have
$$
\begin{aligned}
& \frac{a}{(b+c)^{2}}+\frac{b}{(c+a)^{2}}+\frac{c}{(a+b)^{2}} \\
& \quad \geq \frac{1}{3}\left(\frac{a}{b+c}+\frac{b}{c+a}+\frac{c}{a+b}\right)^{2}+\frac{a}{b+c}+\frac{b}{c+a}+\frac{c}{a+b} \\
& \quad \geq \frac{1}{3}\left(\frac{3}{2}\right)^{2}+\frac{3}{2}=\frac{9}{4}
\end{aligned}
$$

Consider the function $f(t)=\sqrt{t^{2}+1}, t \geq 0$.
Since $f^{\prime \prime}(t)=\frac{1}{\left(\sqrt{t^{2}+1}\right)^{3}}>0, f$ is convex on $[0, \infty)$.
Therefore by Jensen's inequality we have
$$
\frac{\sqrt{x^{2}+1}+\sqrt{y^{2}+1}+\sqrt{z^{2}+1}}{3} \geq \sqrt{\left(\frac{x+y+z}{3}\right)^{2}+1}
$$
i.e.
$$
\begin{equation*}
\sqrt{x^{2}+1}+\sqrt{y^{2}+1}+\sqrt{z^{2}+1} \geq \sqrt{(x+y+z)^{2}+9} \tag{1}
\end{equation*}
$$

From the obvious inequality $((x+y+z)-3)^{2} \geq 0$ it follows that
$$
\begin{equation*}
(x+y+z)^{2}+9 \geq 6(x+y+z) \tag{2}
\end{equation*}
$$

By (1) and (2) we obtain
$$
\sqrt{x^{2}+1}+\sqrt{y^{2}+1}+\sqrt{z^{2}+1} \geq \sqrt{(x+y+z)^{2}+9} \geq \sqrt{6(x+y+z)}
$$

Equality occurs if and only if $x=y=z=1$.

Theorem 43.Theorem:
Let $a_{i} \in(0, \infty), i=1,2, \ldots, n$, and $\alpha_{i} \in[0,1], i=1,2, \ldots, n$, be such that $\alpha_{1}+\alpha_{2}+\cdots+\alpha_{n}=1$.
Then
$$
\begin{equation*}
a_{1}^{\alpha_{1}} a_{2}^{\alpha_{2}} \cdots a_{n}^{\alpha_{n}} \leq a_{1} \alpha_{1}+a_{2} \alpha_{2}+\cdots+a_{n} \alpha_{n} \tag{7.9}
\end{equation*}
$$

Theorem 40.Theorem:
Let $f:(a, b) \rightarrow \mathbb{R}$ be a convex function on the interval $(a, b)$. Let $n \in \mathbb{N}$ and $\alpha_{1}, \alpha_{2}, \ldots, \alpha_{n} \in(0,1)$ be real numbers such that $\alpha_{1}+\alpha_{2}+\cdots+\alpha_{n}=1$. Then for any $x_{1}, x_{2}, \ldots, x_{n} \in(a, b)$ we have
$$
f\left(\sum_{i=1}^{n} \alpha_{i} x_{i}\right) \leq \sum_{i=1}^{n} \alpha_{i} f\left(x_{i}\right)
$$
i.e.
$$
\begin{equation*}
f\left(\alpha_{1} x_{1}+\alpha_{2} x_{2}+\cdots+\alpha_{n} x_{n}\right) \leq \alpha_{1} f\left(x_{1}\right)+\alpha_{2} f\left(x_{2}\right)+\cdots+\alpha_{n} f\left(x_{n}\right) \tag{7.2}
\end{equation*}
$$

solution:
Observe that if $a, b, c>1$ then $a^{2}+b^{2}+c^{2}+a b c>4$.
Therefore at least one number from $a, b$ and $c$ must be less than or equal to 1 . Without loss of generality assume that $a \leq 1$.
Then we have
$$
a b+b c+c a-a b c \geq b c-a b c=b c(1-a) \geq 0
$$

So we have proved the left inequality.
Let $a=2 x, b=2 y, c=2 z$.
Then the condition $a^{2}+b^{2}+c^{2}+a b c=4$ becomes
$$
\begin{equation*}
x^{2}+y^{2}+z^{2}+2 x y z=1 \tag{1}
\end{equation*}
$$
and the given inequality becomes
$$
\begin{equation*}
2 x y+2 y z+2 z x-4 x y z \leq 1 \tag{2}
\end{equation*}
$$

By (1) we can take
$$
x=\cos \alpha, \quad y=\cos \beta, \quad z=\cos \gamma
$$
where $\alpha, \beta, \gamma \in[0, \pi / 2]$ and $\alpha+\beta+\gamma=\pi$.
Therefore inequality (2) becomes
$$
2 \cos \alpha \cos \beta+2 \cos \beta \cos \gamma+2 \cos \gamma \cos \alpha-4 \cos \alpha \cos \beta \cos \gamma \leq 1
$$
i.e.
$$
\begin{equation*}
\cos \alpha \cos \beta+\cos \beta \cos \gamma+\cos \gamma \cos \alpha-2 \cos \alpha \cos \beta \cos \gamma \leq \frac{1}{2} \tag{3}
\end{equation*}
$$

Clearly at least one of the angles $\alpha, \beta$ and $\gamma$ is less than or equal to $\pi / 3$.
Without loss of generality, we may assume $\alpha \geq \pi / 3$ and it follows that $\cos \alpha \leq \frac{1}{2}$. We have
$$
\begin{align*}
& \cos \alpha \cos \beta+\cos \beta \cos \gamma+\cos \gamma \cos \alpha-2 \cos \alpha \cos \beta \cos \gamma \\
& \quad=\cos \alpha(\cos \beta+\cos \gamma)+\cos \beta \cos \gamma(1-2 \cos \alpha) \tag{4}
\end{align*}
$$

We have that
$$
\begin{equation*}
\cos \alpha+\cos \beta+\cos \gamma \leq \frac{3}{2}, \quad \text { i.e. } \quad \cos \beta+\cos \gamma \leq \frac{3}{2}-\cos \alpha \tag{5}
\end{equation*}
$$

Also
$$
\begin{equation*}
2 \cos \beta \cos \gamma=\cos (\beta-\gamma)+\cos (\beta+\gamma) \leq 1+\cos (\beta+\gamma)=1-\cos \alpha \tag{6}
\end{equation*}
$$

By (4), (5) and (6) we obtain
$$
\begin{aligned}
& \cos \alpha \cos \beta+\cos \beta \cos \gamma+\cos \gamma \cos \alpha-2 \cos \alpha \cos \beta \cos \gamma \\
& \quad=\cos \alpha(\cos \beta+\cos \gamma)+\cos \beta \cos \gamma(1-2 \cos \alpha) \\
& \quad \leq \cos \alpha\left(\frac{3}{2}-\cos \alpha\right)+\frac{1-\cos \alpha}{2}(1-2 \cos \alpha)=2
\end{aligned}
$$
as required.

The given inequality is equivalent to
$$
\begin{equation*}
\frac{a}{b}+\frac{b}{c}+\frac{c}{a}+\frac{b}{a}+\frac{c}{b}+\frac{a}{c} \leq 7 \tag{1}
\end{equation*}
$$

Without loss of generality we may assume that $a \geq b \geq c$.
Then, since $(a-b)(b-c) \geq 0$ we deduce that
$$
a b+b c \geq b^{2}+a c, \quad \text { i.e. } \quad \frac{a}{c}+1 \geq \frac{a}{b}+\frac{b}{c}
$$

Analogously as $a b+b c \geq b^{2}+a c$ we have $\frac{c}{a}+1 \geq \frac{c}{b}+\frac{b}{a}$.
Now we obtain
$$
\frac{a}{b}+\frac{b}{c}+\frac{c}{b}+\frac{b}{a} \leq \frac{a}{c}+\frac{c}{a}+2
$$

So
$$
\begin{equation*}
\frac{a}{b}+\frac{b}{c}+\frac{c}{a}+\frac{b}{a}+\frac{c}{b}+\frac{a}{c} \leq 2+2\left(\frac{a}{c}+\frac{c}{a}\right) \tag{2}
\end{equation*}
$$

Let $x=\frac{a}{c}$. Then $2 \geq x \geq 1$, i.e. we have that $(x-2)(x-1) \leq 0$, from which we deduce that
$$
\begin{equation*}
x+\frac{1}{x} \leq \frac{5}{2} \tag{3}
\end{equation*}
$$

Finally using (2) and (3) we obtain inequality (1).
Equality occurs iff $a=b=2, c=1$ or $a=2, b=c=1$.

Theorem 36.Theorem:
Let $a_{1} \leq a_{2} \leq \cdots \leq a_{n}$ and $b_{1} \leq$ $b_{2} \leq \cdots \leq b_{n}$ be real numbers. For any permutation $\left(x_{1}, x_{2}, \ldots, x_{n}\right)$ of $\left(a_{1}, a_{2}, \ldots, a_{n}\right)$ we have the following inequalities:
$$
\begin{aligned}
a_{1} b_{1}+a_{2} b_{2}+\cdots+a_{n} b_{n} & \geq x_{1} b_{1}+x_{2} b_{2}+\cdots+x_{n} b_{n} \\
& \geq a_{n} b_{1}+a_{n-1} b_{2}+\cdots+a_{1} b_{n}
\end{aligned}
$$

Theorem 56.Theorem:
Let $a_{1}, a_{2}, \ldots, a_{n}$ and $b_{1}, b_{2}, \ldots, b_{n}$ be two sequences of nonnegative real numbers and $c_{i}>0, i=1,2, \ldots, n$, such that $\frac{a_{1}}{c_{1}} \geq \frac{a_{2}}{c_{2}} \geq \cdots \geq$ $\frac{a_{n}}{c_{n}}$ and $\frac{b_{1}}{c_{1}} \geq \frac{b_{2}}{c_{2}} \geq \cdots \geq \frac{b_{n}}{c_{n}}$ (the sequences $\left(\frac{a_{i}}{c_{i}}\right)$ and $\left(\frac{b_{i}}{c_{i}}\right)$ have the same orientation). Then
$$
\begin{equation*}
\sum_{i=1}^{n} \frac{a_{i} b_{i}}{c_{i}} \geq \frac{\sum_{i=1}^{n} a_{i} \cdot \sum_{i=1}^{n} b_{i}}{\sum_{i=1}^{n} c_{i}} \tag{10.1}
\end{equation*}
$$
i.e.
$$
\frac{a_{1} b_{1}}{c_{1}}+\frac{a_{2} b_{2}}{c_{2}}+\cdots+\frac{a_{n} b_{n}}{c_{n}} \geq \frac{\left(a_{1}+a_{2}+\cdots+a_{n}\right)\left(b_{1}+b_{2}+\cdots+b_{n}\right)}{c_{1}+c_{2}+\cdots+c_{n}}
$$

solution:
First we'll show that
$$
\begin{equation*}
a^{2} b^{2}+b^{2} c^{2}+c^{2} a^{2} \geq a^{2} b^{2} c^{2} \tag{1}
\end{equation*}
$$

We have
$$
(a b)^{2}+(b c)^{2}+(c a)^{2} \geq(a b)(b c)+(b c)(c a)+(c a)(a b)=a b c(a+b+c)
$$
i.e.
$$
\begin{aligned}
& \frac{1}{a^{2}}+\frac{1}{b^{2}}+\frac{1}{c^{2}}=\frac{(a b)^{2}+(b c)^{2}+(c a)^{2}}{(a b c)^{2}} \geq \frac{a+b+c}{a b c}=1 \\
& \quad \Leftrightarrow \quad a^{2} b^{2}+b^{2} c^{2}+c^{2} a^{2} \geq a^{2} b^{2} c^{2}
\end{aligned}
$$

Furthermore
$$
\begin{align*}
(a b+b c+c a)^{2} & =a^{2} b^{2}+b^{2} c^{2}+c^{2} a^{2}+2 a b c(a+b+c) \\
& \stackrel{(1)}{\geq} a^{2} b^{2} c^{2}+2 a b c(a+b+c)=3(a+b+c)^{2} \tag{2}
\end{align*}
$$

So
$$
\begin{aligned}
(a b+b c+c a-3)^{2} & =(a b+b c+c a)^{2}-6(a b+b c+c a)+9 \\
& \stackrel{(2)}{\geq} 3(a+b+c)^{2}-6(a b+b c+c a)+9 \\
& =3\left(a^{2}+b^{2}+c^{2}\right)+9
\end{aligned}
$$
i.e.
$$
\begin{equation*}
a b+b c+c a \geq 3+\sqrt{3\left(a^{2}+b^{2}+c^{2}\right)+9} \tag{3}
\end{equation*}
$$

Applying the Cauchy-Schwarz inequality we have
$$
\begin{aligned}
3\left(a^{2}+b^{2}+c^{2}\right)+9 & =3\left(\left(a^{2}+1\right)+\left(b^{2}+1\right)+\left(c^{2}+1\right)\right) \\
& \geq\left(\sqrt{a^{2}+1}+\sqrt{b^{2}+1}+\sqrt{c^{2}+1}\right)^{2}
\end{aligned}
$$
i.e.
$$
\begin{equation*}
\sqrt{3\left(a^{2}+b^{2}+c^{2}\right)+9} \geq \sqrt{a^{2}+1}+\sqrt{b^{2}+1}+\sqrt{c^{2}+1} \tag{4}
\end{equation*}
$$

Using (3) and (4) we obtain
$a b+b c+c a \geq 3+\sqrt{3\left(a^{2}+b^{2}+c^{2}\right)+9} \geq 3+\sqrt{a^{2}+1}+\sqrt{b^{2}+1}+\sqrt{c^{2}+1}$, as required.

Theorem 5.Theorem:
For any real numbers $a_{1}, a_{2}, \ldots, a_{n}$ and $b_{1}, b_{2}, \ldots, b_{n}$

$$
