$$

So it is enough to show that
$$
\begin{equation*}
3 p^{2}-6 q+4-q \geq 10, \quad \text { i.e. } \quad 3 p^{2}-7 q-6 \geq 0 \tag{1}
\end{equation*}
$$

Applying $N_{1}: p^{3}-4 p q+9 r \geq 0$ (Chap. 14), and since $q+r=4$ we deuce
$$
p^{3}-4 p q+9(4-q) \geq 0, \quad \text { i.e. } \quad q \leq \frac{p^{3}+36}{4 p+9}
$$

So
$$
\begin{equation*}
3 p^{2}-7 q-6 \geq 3 p^{2}-7 \frac{p^{3}+36}{4 p+9}-6=\frac{(p-3)\left(5 p^{2}+42 p+102\right)}{4 p+9} \tag{2}
\end{equation*}
$$

Applying $A M \geq G M$ we obtain
