Theorem 70.Theorem:
Let $f:[a, b] \rightarrow \mathbb{R}$ and $g:[a, b] \rightarrow \mathbb{R}$ be functions such that:
(i) $f$ and $g$ are continuous on $[a, b]$ and $f(a)=g(a)$;
(ii) $f$ and $g$ are differentiable on $(a, b)$;
(iii) $f^{\prime}(x)>g^{\prime}(x)$, for all $x \in(a, b)$.

Then, for all $x \in(a, b)$, we have $f(x)>g(x)$.

solution:
Denote $A=\frac{x^{2}+1}{x+1}$.
We have
$$
\begin{equation*}
A=\frac{x^{2}-1+2}{x+1}=(x-1)+\frac{2}{x+1}=\left((x+1)+\frac{2}{x+1}\right)-2 \tag{1}
\end{equation*}
$$

For any $a, b \geq 0$ we have $a+b \geq 2 \sqrt{a b}$ (equality occurs iff $a=b$ ).
Now from (1) we get $A \geq 2 \sqrt{2}-2$.
Equality occurs if and only if $x=\sqrt{2}-1$.

With the same notations, we have to prove that

$$
\begin{gathered}
