$$

Theorem 5.Theorem:
For any real numbers $a_{1}, a_{2}, \ldots, a_{n}$ and $b_{1}, b_{2}, \ldots, b_{n}$

$$
\begin{gathered}
\left(a_{1}^{2}+a_{2}^{2}+\ldots+a_{n}^{2}\right)\left(b_{1}^{2}+b_{2}^{2}+\ldots+b_{n}^{2}\right) \geq \\
\geq\left(a_{1} b_{1}+a_{2} b_{2}+\ldots+a_{n} b_{n}\right)^{2}
\end{gathered}
$$

with equality if and only if $a_{i}$ and $b_{i}$ are proportional, $i=1,2, \ldots, n$.

solution:
Since
$$
a^{4}-a^{3} b-a b^{3}+b^{4}=a^{3}(a-b)-b^{3}(a-b)=(a-b)^{2}\left(a^{2}-a b+b^{2}\right) \geq 0
$$
we have
$$
a^{5}+b^{5}=(a+b)\left(a^{4}-a^{3} b+a^{2} b^{2}-a b^{3}+b^{4}\right) \geq(a+b) a^{2} b^{2}
$$

So
$$
\begin{equation*}
\frac{a b}{a^{5}+a b+b^{5}} \leq \frac{a b}{(a+b) a^{2} b^{2}+a b}=\frac{a b c^{2}}{(a+b) a^{2} b^{2} c^{2}+a b c^{2}}=\frac{c}{a+b+c} \tag{1}
\end{equation*}
$$

Analogously
$$
\begin{equation*}
\frac{b c}{b^{5}+b c+c^{5}} \leq \frac{a}{a+b+c} \tag{2}
\end{equation*}
$$
and
$$
\begin{equation*}
\frac{c a}{c^{5}+c a+a^{5}} \leq \frac{b}{a+b+c} \tag{3}
\end{equation*}
$$

Adding (1), (2) and (3) gives us the required inequality.

Applying $A M \geq G M$ we have
$$
\begin{aligned}
\frac{a}{1+b^{2} c} & =a-\frac{a b^{2} c}{1+b^{2} c} \geq a-\frac{a b^{2} c}{2 b \sqrt{c}}=a-\frac{a b \sqrt{c}}{2} \geq a-\frac{b \sqrt{a \cdot a c}}{2} \\
& \geq a-\frac{b(a+a c)}{4}
\end{aligned}
$$
i.e.
$$
\frac{a}{1+b^{2} c} \geq a-\frac{1}{4}(a b+a b c)
$$

Analogously we obtain
$$
\begin{aligned}
& \frac{b}{1+c^{2} d} \geq b-\frac{1}{4}(b c+b c d), \quad \frac{c}{1+d^{2} a} \geq c-\frac{1}{4}(c d+c d a), \\
& \frac{d}{1+a^{2} b} \geq d-\frac{1}{4}(d a+d a b) .
\end{aligned}
$$

Adding these three inequalities we obtain
$$
\begin{align*}
& \frac{a}{1+b^{2} c}+\frac{b}{1+c^{2} d}+\frac{c}{1+d^{2} a}+\frac{d}{1+a^{2} b}  \tag{1}\\
& \quad \geq(a+b+c+d)-\frac{1}{4}(a b+b c+c d+d a+a b c+b c d+c d a+d a b)
\end{align*}
$$

One more use of $A M \geq G M$ give us
$$
\begin{equation*}
a b+b c+c d+d a \leq \frac{1}{4}(a+b+c+d)^{2}=4 \tag{2}
\end{equation*}
$$
and
$$
\begin{equation*}
a b c+b c d+c d a+d a b \leq \frac{1}{16}(a+b+c+d)^{3}=4 . \tag{3}
\end{equation*}
$$

From (1), (2) and (3) it follows that
$$
\frac{a}{1+b^{2} c}+\frac{b}{1+c^{2} d}+\frac{c}{1+d^{2} a}+\frac{d}{1+a^{2} b} \geq 4-2=2
$$
as desired.
