$$

with equality if and only if $a_{i}$ and $b_{i}$ are proportional, $i=1,2, \ldots, n$.

solution:
Using the identity
$$
(a+b)(b+c)(c+a)=(a+b+c)(a b+b c+c a)-1
$$
the given inequality becomes
$$
a b+b c+c a+\frac{3}{a+b+c} \geq 4
$$

By $A M \geq G M$ we have
$a b+b c+c a+\frac{3}{a+b+c}=\frac{3(a b+b c+c a)}{3}+\frac{3}{a+b+c} \geq 4 \sqrt[4]{\frac{(a b+b c+c a)^{3}}{9(a+b+c)}}$.
So it's enough to show that
$$
\begin{equation*}
(a b+b c+c a)^{3} \geq 9(a+b+c) \tag{1}
\end{equation*}
$$

By $A M \geq G M$ and $a b c=1$ we get
$$
\begin{equation*}
a b+b c+c a \geq 3 \sqrt[3]{(a b c)^{2}}=3 \tag{2}
\end{equation*}
$$

Furthermore, since $(x+y+z)^{2} \geq 3(x y+y z+z x)$, we deduce
$$
\begin{equation*}
(a b+b c+c a)^{2} \geq 3((a b)(b c)+(b c)(c a)+(c a)(a b))=3(a+b+c) \tag{3}
\end{equation*}
$$

By (2) and (3) we obtain $(a b+b c+c a)^{3} \geq 9(a+b+c)$, i.e. (1) is true.

Let $p=a+b+c, q=a b+b c+c a, r=a b c$.
Since the given inequality is homogenous, without loss of generality we may assume that $p=1$.

We have
$$
\begin{aligned}
x^{4}(y+z)+y^{4}(z+x)+z^{4}(x+y) & =x^{3}(x y+x z)+y^{3}(y z+y x)+z^{3}(z x+z y) \\
& =x^{3}(q-y z)+y^{3}(q-z x)+z^{3}(q-x y) \\
& =q\left(x^{3}+y^{3}+z^{3}\right)-x y z\left(x^{2}+y^{2}+z^{2}\right) \\
& =q\left(p\left(p^{2}-3 q\right)+3 r\right)-r\left(p^{2}-2 q\right) \\
& =q(1-3 q+3 r)-r(1-2 q) \\
& =q(1-3 q)+r(5 q-1) .
\end{aligned}
$$

Now the given inequality becomes
$$
\begin{equation*}
q(1-3 q)+r(5 q-1) \leq \frac{1}{12} \tag{1}
\end{equation*}
$$

From $3 q \leq p^{2}$ it follows that
$$
\begin{equation*}
q \leq \frac{1}{3} \tag{2}
\end{equation*}
$$

If $q \leq \frac{1}{5}$ then $r(5 q-1) \leq 0$, so we have
$q(1-3 q)+r(5 q-1) \leq q(1-3 q)=\frac{1}{3}(1-3 q) \cdot 3 q \stackrel{G \leq A}{\leq} \frac{1}{3}\left(\frac{(1-3 q)+3 q}{2}\right)^{2}=\frac{1}{12}$,
i.e. inequality (1) holds.

Let
$$
\begin{equation*}
q>\frac{1}{5} \tag{3}
\end{equation*}
$$
i.e. let $q \in(1 / 5,1 / 3]$ and denote
$$
f(q)=q(1-3 q)+5 r q-r
$$

Then
$$
\begin{equation*}
f^{\prime}(q)=1-6 q+5 r \tag{4}
\end{equation*}
$$

Using $p q \geq 9 r$ , we get
$$
\begin{equation*}
q \geq 9 r \tag{5}
\end{equation*}
$$

Now according to (3), (4) and (5) we deduce
$$
f^{\prime}(q)=1-6 q+5 r \leq 1-6 q+\frac{5}{9} q=1-\frac{49}{9} q<1-\frac{49}{9} \cdot \frac{1}{5}<0
$$
i.e. $f$ is strictly decreasing on $q \in(1 / 5,1 / 3]$, so it follows that $f(q)<f\left(\frac{1}{5}\right)$, i.e. we deduce that
$$
q(1-3 q)+r(5 q-1)<\frac{1}{5}\left(1-\frac{3}{5}\right)+r\left(5 \frac{1}{5}-1\right)=\frac{2}{25}<\frac{1}{12}
$$
as required.

At the point of incidence $a=b=c=1$ we have $5 a^{2}+4(b+c)+3=16$. By the inequality $A M \geq G M$ we get
$$
\begin{aligned}
