Theorem 5.Theorem:
For any real numbers $a_{1}, a_{2}, \ldots, a_{n}$ and $b_{1}, b_{2}, \ldots, b_{n}$

$$
\begin{gathered}
\left(a_{1}^{2}+a_{2}^{2}+\ldots+a_{n}^{2}\right)\left(b_{1}^{2}+b_{2}^{2}+\ldots+b_{n}^{2}\right) \geq \\
\geq\left(a_{1} b_{1}+a_{2} b_{2}+\ldots+a_{n} b_{n}\right)^{2}
\end{gathered}
$$

with equality if and only if $a_{i}$ and $b_{i}$ are proportional, $i=1,2, \ldots, n$.

solution:
By the well-known inequalities:
$$
x^{2}+y^{2} \geq 2 x y \quad \text { and } \quad 3\left(x^{2}+y^{2}+z^{2}\right) \geq(x+y+z)^{2}
$$
we obtain
$$
\begin{align*}
& \frac{b^{2}+c^{2}}{a}+\frac{c^{2}+a^{2}}{b}+\frac{a^{2}+b^{2}}{c} \\
& \quad \geq \frac{2 b c}{a}+\frac{2 c a}{b}+\frac{2 a b}{c}=\frac{2\left((b c)^{2}+(c a)^{2}+(a b)^{2}\right)}{a b c} \geq \frac{2(b c+c a+a b)^{2}}{3 a b c} \tag{1}
\end{align*}
$$

We have
$$
(a b+b c+c a)^{2} \geq 3((a b)(b c)+(b c)(c a)+(c a)(a b))=3 a b c(a+b+c)
$$
i.e.
$$
\begin{equation*}
a b+b c+c a \geq \sqrt{3 a b c(a+b+c)} \tag{2}
\end{equation*}
$$

Also
$$
4 a b c=a+b+c+1 \geq 4 \sqrt[4]{a b c}
$$
i.e.
$$
\begin{equation*}
a b c \geq 1 \tag{3}
\end{equation*}
$$

Therefore
$$
\begin{equation*}
a+b+c=4 a b c-1=3 a b c+a b c-1 \stackrel{(3)}{\geq} 3 a b c \tag{4}
\end{equation*}
$$

By (1), (2) and (4) we obtain
$$
\begin{aligned}
& \frac{b^{2}+c^{2}}{a}+\frac{c^{2}+a^{2}}{b}+\frac{a^{2}+b^{2}}{c} \\
& \geq \frac{2(b c+c a+a b)^{2}}{3 a b c} \geq \frac{2(a b+b c+c a) \sqrt{3 a b c(a+b+c)}}{3 a b c} \\
& \geq \frac{2(a b+b c+c a) \sqrt{(3 a b c)^{2}}}{3 a b c}=2(a b+b c+c a) .
\end{aligned}
$$

Applying the Cauchy-Schwarz Inequality gives

$$
\begin{equation*}
3\left(a^{2}+b^{2}+c^{2}\right) \geq 3(a+b+c)^{2} \tag{1}
\end{equation*}
$$

and

$$
\begin{equation*}
\left(a^{2}+b^{2}+c^{2}\right)^{2} \leq(a+b+c)\left(a^{3}+b^{3}+c^{3}\right) \tag{2}
\end{equation*}
$$

These two inequalities combined yield

$$
\begin{align*}
a^{3}+b^{3}+c^{3} & \geq \frac{\left(a^{2}+b^{2}+c^{2}\right)(a+b+c)}{3} \\
& =\frac{\left(a^{2}+b^{2}+c^{2}\right)[(b+c)+(a+c)+(a+b)]}{6} \\
& \geq \frac{(a \sqrt{b+c}+b \sqrt{a+c}+c \sqrt{a+b})^{2}}{6} \tag{3}
\end{align*}
$$

Using the AM-GM Inequality we obtain

$$
\begin{aligned}
a \sqrt{b+c}+b \sqrt{a+c}+c \sqrt{a+b} & \geq 3 \sqrt[3]{a b c(\sqrt{(a+b)(b+c)(c+a)})} \\
& \geq 3 \sqrt[3]{a b c \sqrt{8 a b c}}=3 \sqrt[3]{8}=6
\end{aligned}
$$

Thus

$$
\begin{equation*}
(a \sqrt{b+c}+b \sqrt{a+c}+c \sqrt{a+b})^{2} \geq 6(a \sqrt{b+c}+b \sqrt{a+c}+c \sqrt{a+b}) \tag{4}
\end{equation*}
$$

The desired inequality follows from (3) and (4).

