Theorem 40.Theorem:
Let $f:(a, b) \rightarrow \mathbb{R}$ be a convex function on the interval $(a, b)$. Let $n \in \mathbb{N}$ and $\alpha_{1}, \alpha_{2}, \ldots, \alpha_{n} \in(0,1)$ be real numbers such that $\alpha_{1}+\alpha_{2}+\cdots+\alpha_{n}=1$. Then for any $x_{1}, x_{2}, \ldots, x_{n} \in(a, b)$ we have
$$
f\left(\sum_{i=1}^{n} \alpha_{i} x_{i}\right) \leq \sum_{i=1}^{n} \alpha_{i} f\left(x_{i}\right)
$$
i.e.
$$
\begin{equation*}
f\left(\alpha_{1} x_{1}+\alpha_{2} x_{2}+\cdots+\alpha_{n} x_{n}\right) \leq \alpha_{1} f\left(x_{1}\right)+\alpha_{2} f\left(x_{2}\right)+\cdots+\alpha_{n} f\left(x_{n}\right) \tag{7.2}
\end{equation*}
$$

solution:
We have $2 c d \leq c^{2}+d^{2}=1-a^{2}-b^{2}$.
Hence
$$
2(1-a)(1-b)-2 c d \geq 2(1-a)(1-b)-1+a^{2}+b^{2}=(1-a-b)^{2} \geq 0
$$
i.e.
$$
\begin{equation*}
(1-a)(1-b) \geq c d \tag{1}
\end{equation*}
$$

Similarly we get
$$
\begin{equation*}
(1-c)(1-d) \geq a b \tag{2}
\end{equation*}
$$

After multiplying (1) and (2) we obtain $(1-a)(1-b)(1-c)(1-d) \geq a b c d$, as required. Equality occurs iff $a=b=c=d=1 / 2$ or $a=1, b=c=d=0$ (up to permutation).

Let $x=b / a, y=c / b, z=d / c$ and $t=a / d$.
Then it is clear that $x y z t=1$, and the given inequality becomes
$$
\begin{equation*}
A=\left(\frac{1}{1+x}\right)^{5}+\left(\frac{1}{1+y}\right)^{5}+\left(\frac{1}{1+z}\right)^{5}+\left(\frac{1}{1+t}\right)^{5} \geq \frac{1}{8} \tag{1}
\end{equation*}
$$

By the inequality $A M \geq G M$ we have
$$
2\left(\frac{1}{1+x}\right)^{5}+\frac{3}{32}=\left(\frac{1}{1+x}\right)^{5}+\left(\frac{1}{1+x}\right)^{5}+\frac{1}{32}+\frac{1}{32}+\frac{1}{32} \geq \frac{5}{8}\left(\frac{1}{1+x}\right)^{2}
$$
i.e.
$$
2\left(\frac{1}{1+x}\right)^{5}+\frac{3}{32} \geq \frac{5}{8}\left(\frac{1}{1+x}\right)^{2}
$$

So it follows that
$$
\begin{equation*}
2 A+\frac{12}{32} \geq \frac{5}{8}\left(\left(\frac{1}{1+x}\right)^{2}+\left(\frac{1}{1+y}\right)^{2}+\left(\frac{1}{1+z}\right)^{2}+\left(\frac{1}{1+t}\right)^{2}\right) \tag{2}
\end{equation*}
$$

We'll prove that for all positive real numbers $x$ and $y$ the following inequality holds
$$
\frac{1}{(1+x)^{2}}+\frac{1}{(1+y)^{2}} \geq \frac{1}{1+x y}
$$

We have
$$
\begin{aligned}
\frac{1}{(1+x)^{2}}+\frac{1}{(1+y)^{2}}-\frac{1}{1+x y} & =\frac{x y\left(x^{2}+y^{2}\right)-x^{2} y^{2}-2 x y+1}{(1+x)^{2}(1+y)^{2}(1+x y)} \\
& =\frac{x y(x-y)^{2}+(x y-1)^{2}}{(1+x)^{2}(1+y)^{2}(1+x y)} \geq 0
\end{aligned}
$$

Now according to the previous inequality and the condition $x y z t=1$, we deduce
$$
\begin{align*}
& \left(\frac{1}{1+x}\right)^{2}+\left(\frac{1}{1+y}\right)^{2}+\left(\frac{1}{1+z}\right)^{2}+\left(\frac{1}{1+t}\right)^{2} \\
& \geq \frac{1}{1+x y}+\frac{1}{1+z t}=\frac{1}{1+x y}+\frac{1}{1+1 / x y}=1 \tag{3}
\end{align*}
$$

By (2) and (3) we get
$$
2 A+\frac{12}{32} \geq \frac{5}{8}, \quad \text { i.e. } \quad A \geq \frac{1}{8}
$$

Equality occurs iff $x=y=z=t=1$, i.e. $a=b=c=d$.

By $A M \geq H M$ we get
$$
a+b+c \geq \frac{1}{a}+\frac{1}{b}+\frac{1}{c} \geq \frac{9}{a+b+c}
$$
i.e.
$$
\begin{equation*}
\frac{a+b+c}{3} \geq \frac{3}{a+b+c} \tag{1}
\end{equation*}
$$

We will prove that
$$
\begin{equation*}
\frac{2(a+b+c)}{3} \geq \frac{2}{a b c} \tag{2}
\end{equation*}
$$
i.e.
$$
a+b+c \geq \frac{3}{a b c}
$$

Using the well-known inequality $(x y+y z+z x)^{2} \geq 3(x y+y z+z x)$ we obtain
$$
(a+b+c)^{2} \geq\left(\frac{1}{a}+\frac{1}{b}+\frac{1}{c}\right)^{2} \geq 3\left(\frac{1}{a b}+\frac{1}{b c}+\frac{1}{c a}\right)=3 \frac{a+b+c}{a b c}
$$
i.e.
$$
a+b+c \geq \frac{3}{a b c}
$$

After adding (1) and (2) we get the required inequality.

Theorem 5.Theorem:
For any real numbers $a_{1}, a_{2}, \ldots, a_{n}$ and $b_{1}, b_{2}, \ldots, b_{n}$

$$
\begin{gathered}
\left(a_{1}^{2}+a_{2}^{2}+\ldots+a_{n}^{2}\right)\left(b_{1}^{2}+b_{2}^{2}+\ldots+b_{n}^{2}\right) \geq \\
\geq\left(a_{1} b_{1}+a_{2} b_{2}+\ldots+a_{n} b_{n}\right)^{2}
\end{gathered}
$$

with equality if and only if $a_{i}$ and $b_{i}$ are proportional, $i=1,2, \ldots, n$.

solution:
By the inequality $A M \geq H M$ we have
$$
\begin{equation*}
((3+a)+(3+b)+(3+c))\left(\frac{1}{3+a}+\frac{1}{3+b}+\frac{1}{3+c}\right) \geq 9 \tag{1}
\end{equation*}
$$
and
$$
\begin{align*}
& ((3-a)+(3-b)+(3-c))\left(\frac{1}{3-a}+\frac{1}{3-b}+\frac{1}{3-c}\right) \geq 9 \\
& \quad \Leftrightarrow \quad((3-a)+(3-b)+(3-c))\left(\frac{1}{3+a}+\frac{1}{3+b}+\frac{1}{3+c}\right) \geq 9 \tag{2}
\end{align*}
$$

After adding (1) and (2) we obtain
$$
18\left(\frac{1}{3+a}+\frac{1}{3+b}+\frac{1}{3+c}\right) \geq 18, \quad \text { i.e. } \quad \frac{1}{3+a}+\frac{1}{3+b}+\frac{1}{3+c} \geq 1
$$

We can easily show the inequalities
$$
t_{a}<\frac{b+c}{2}, \quad t_{b}<\frac{a+c}{2}, \quad t_{c}<\frac{b+a}{2}
$$

After adding these we get
$$
\begin{equation*}
t_{a}+t_{b}+t_{c}<a+b+c \tag{1}
\end{equation*}
$$

By squaring (1) we deduce
$$
\begin{equation*}
t_{a}^{2}+t_{b}^{2}+t_{c}^{2}+2\left(t_{a} t_{b}+t_{b} t_{c}+t_{c} t_{a}\right)<a^{2}+b^{2}+c^{2}+2(a b+b c+c a) \tag{2}
\end{equation*}
$$

On the other hand, we have
$$
t_{a}^{2}=\frac{2\left(b^{2}+c^{2}\right)-a^{2}}{4}, \quad t_{b}^{2}=\frac{2\left(a^{2}+c^{2}\right)-b^{2}}{4}, \quad t_{c}^{2}=\frac{2\left(b^{2}+a^{2}\right)-c^{2}}{4}
$$
so
$$
t_{a}^{2}+t_{b}^{2}+t_{c}^{2}=\frac{3}{4}\left(a^{2}+b^{2}+c^{2}\right)
$$

Now using the previous result and (2) we get
$$
\begin{equation*}
t_{a} t_{b}+t_{b} t_{c}+t_{c} t_{a}<\frac{1}{8}\left(a^{2}+b^{2}+c^{2}\right)+(a b+b c+c a) \tag{3}
\end{equation*}
$$

Also we have $a^{2}+b^{2}+c^{2}<2(a b+b c+c a)$, since
$a^{2}+b^{2}+c^{2}-2(a b+b c+c a)=a(a-b-c)+b(b-a-c)+c(c-a-b)<0$.
Finally by (3) and the previous inequality we obtain
$$
t_{a} t_{b}+t_{b} t_{c}+t_{c} t_{a}<\frac{5}{4}(a b+b c+c a)
$$

We have
$$
\begin{align*}
\left(a^{2}+b^{2}+c^{2}\right)^{2} & =a^{4}+b^{4}+c^{4}+2 a^{2} b^{2}+2 b^{2} c^{2}+2 c^{2} a^{2} \\
& =a^{4}+b^{4}+c^{4}+a^{2}\left(b^{2}+c^{2}\right)+b^{2}\left(c^{2}+a^{2}\right)+c^{2}\left(a^{2}+b^{2}\right) \tag{1}
\end{align*}
$$

By Exercise 1.7, it follows that
$$
\begin{equation*}
a^{4}+b^{4}+c^{4} \geq a b c(a+b+c) \tag{2}
\end{equation*}
$$

Also
$$
\begin{equation*}
b^{2}+c^{2} \geq 2 b c, \quad c^{2}+a^{2} \geq 2 c a, \quad a^{2}+b^{2} \geq 2 a b \tag{3}
\end{equation*}
$$

Now by (1), (2) and (3) we deduce
$$
\begin{align*}
\left(a^{2}+b^{2}+c^{2}\right)^{2} & \geq a b c(a+b+c)+2 a^{2} b c+2 b^{2} a c+2 c^{2} a b \\
& =a b c(a+b+c)+2 a b c(a+b+c)=3 a b c(a+b+c) \tag{4}
\end{align*}
$$

Since $a+b+c \geq a b c$ in (4) we have
$$
\left(a^{2}+b^{2}+c^{2}\right)^{2} \geq 3 a b c(a+b+c) \geq 3(a b c)^{2}
$$
i.e.
$$
a^{2}+b^{2}+c^{2} \geq \sqrt{3} a b c .
$$

Equality occurs if and only if $a=b=c=\sqrt{3}$.

The given inequality is equivalent to
$$
\frac{c(a+b)+a b}{a(a+b)}+\frac{a(b+c)+b c}{b(b+c)}+\frac{b(c+a)+a c}{c(c+a)} \geq \frac{9}{2}
$$
i.e.
$$
\begin{align*}
\frac{a}{b} & +\frac{b}{c}+\frac{c}{a}+\frac{b}{a+b}+\frac{c}{b+c}+\frac{a}{c+a} \geq \frac{9}{2} \\
& \Leftrightarrow \quad \frac{a+b}{b}+\frac{b+c}{c}+\frac{c+a}{a}+\frac{b}{a+b}+\frac{c}{b+c}+\frac{a}{c+a} \geq \frac{15}{2} \tag{1}
\end{align*}
$$

We have
$$
\begin{aligned}
& \frac{a+b}{b}+\frac{b+c}{c}+\frac{c+a}{a}+\frac{b}{a+b}+\frac{c}{b+c}+\frac{a}{c+a} \\
& \quad=\frac{a+b}{4 b}+\frac{b+c}{4 c}+\frac{c+a}{4 a}+\frac{b}{a+b}+\frac{c}{b+c}+\frac{a}{c+a}
\end{aligned}
$$
$$
\begin{aligned}
& +\frac{3}{4}\left(\frac{a+b}{b}+\frac{b+c}{c}+\frac{c+a}{a}\right) \\
\geq & 6 \sqrt[6]{\frac{a+b}{4 b} \cdot \frac{b+c}{4 c} \cdot \frac{c+a}{4 a} \cdot \frac{b}{a+b} \cdot \frac{c}{b+c} \cdot \frac{a}{c+a}}+\frac{3}{4}\left(\frac{a}{b}+\frac{b}{c}+\frac{c}{a}+3\right) \\
\geq & 3+\frac{3}{4}\left(3 \sqrt[3]{\frac{a}{b} \cdot \frac{b}{c} \cdot \frac{c}{a}}+3\right)=3+\frac{18}{4}=\frac{15}{2}
\end{aligned}
$$
as required.

Theorem 40.Theorem:
Let $f:(a, b) \rightarrow \mathbb{R}$ be a convex function on the interval $(a, b)$. Let $n \in \mathbb{N}$ and $\alpha_{1}, \alpha_{2}, \ldots, \alpha_{n} \in(0,1)$ be real numbers such that $\alpha_{1}+\alpha_{2}+\cdots+\alpha_{n}=1$. Then for any $x_{1}, x_{2}, \ldots, x_{n} \in(a, b)$ we have
$$
f\left(\sum_{i=1}^{n} \alpha_{i} x_{i}\right) \leq \sum_{i=1}^{n} \alpha_{i} f\left(x_{i}\right)
$$
i.e.
$$
\begin{equation*}
f\left(\alpha_{1} x_{1}+\alpha_{2} x_{2}+\cdots+\alpha_{n} x_{n}\right) \leq \alpha_{1} f\left(x_{1}\right)+\alpha_{2} f\left(x_{2}\right)+\cdots+\alpha_{n} f\left(x_{n}\right) \tag{7.2}
\end{equation*}
$$

solution:
The function $f:(0,+\infty) \rightarrow(0,+\infty)$ defined by $f(x)=\sqrt{x}$ is concave on $(0,+\infty)$, so by Jensen's inequality, for
$$
n=4, \quad \alpha_{1}=\frac{1}{10}, \quad \alpha_{2}=\frac{2}{10}, \quad \alpha_{3}=\frac{3}{10}, \quad \alpha_{4}=\frac{4}{10}
$$
we get
$$
\frac{1}{10} \sqrt{a}+\frac{2}{10} \sqrt{\frac{b}{4}}+\frac{3}{10} \sqrt{\frac{c}{9}}+\frac{4}{10} \sqrt{\frac{d}{16}} \leq \sqrt{\frac{a}{10}+\frac{b}{20}+\frac{c}{30}+\frac{d}{40}}
$$
i.e.
$$
\begin{equation*}
\sqrt{a}+\sqrt{b}+\sqrt{c}+\sqrt{d} \leq 10 \sqrt{\frac{12 a+6 b+4 c+3 d}{120}} \tag{1}
\end{equation*}
$$

On the other hand, we have
$$
\begin{aligned}
& 12 a+6 b+4 c+3 d \\
& \quad=3(a+b+c+d)+(a+b+c)+2(a+b)+6 a \\
& \quad \leq 3 \cdot 30+14+2 \cdot 5+6 \cdot 1=120
\end{aligned}
$$

By (1) and the last inequality we obtain the required result.

