Similarly we get
$$
\frac{y^{5}-y^{2}}{y^{5}+z^{2}+x^{2}} \geq \frac{2 y^{4}-y^{2}\left(z^{2}+x^{2}\right)}{2 y^{4}+\left(z^{2}+x^{2}\right)^{2}} \quad \text { and } \quad \frac{z^{5}-z^{2}}{z^{5}+x^{2}+y^{2}} \geq \frac{2 z^{4}-z^{2}\left(x^{2}+y^{2}\right)}{2 z^{4}+\left(x^{2}+y^{2}\right)^{2}}
$$

So it suffices to show that
$$
\begin{equation*}
\frac{2 x^{4}-x^{2}\left(y^{2}+z^{2}\right)}{2 x^{4}+\left(y^{2}+z^{2}\right)^{2}}+\frac{2 y^{4}-y^{2}\left(z^{2}+x^{2}\right)}{2 y^{4}+\left(z^{2}+x^{2}\right)^{2}}+\frac{2 z^{4}-z^{2}\left(x^{2}+y^{2}\right)}{2 z^{4}+\left(x^{2}+y^{2}\right)^{2}} \geq 0 \tag{1}
\end{equation*}
$$

Let $x^{2}=a, y^{2}=b, z^{2}=c$. Then inequality (1) becomes
$$
\begin{equation*}
\frac{2 a^{2}-a(b+c)}{2 a^{2}+(b+c)^{2}}+\frac{2 b^{2}-b(c+a)}{2 b^{2}+(c+a)^{2}}+\frac{2 c^{2}-c(a+b)}{2 c^{2}+(a+b)^{2}} \geq 0 \tag{2}
\end{equation*}
$$

After some algebraic operations we can rewrite inequality (2) as follows
$$
\begin{aligned}
& (b-c)^{2} \frac{a^{2}+a(b+c)+b^{2}-b c+c^{2}}{\left(2 b^{2}+(c+a)^{2}\right)\left(2 c^{2}+(a+b)^{2}\right)} \\
& \quad+(c-a)^{2} \frac{b^{2}+b(a+c)+c^{2}-c a+a^{2}}{\left(2 a^{2}+(b+c)^{2}\right)\left(2 c^{2}+(a+b)^{2}\right)} \\
& \quad+(a-b)^{2} \frac{c^{2}+c(a+b)+a^{2}-a b+b^{2}}{\left(2 a^{2}+(b+c)^{2}\right)\left(2 b^{2}+(c+a)^{2}\right)} \geq 0
\end{aligned}
$$
which is true due to the obvious inequality: if $x, y \in \mathbb{R}$ then $x^{2}-x y+y^{2} \geq 0$.

Theorem 5.Theorem:
For any real numbers $a_{1}, a_{2}, \ldots, a_{n}$ and $b_{1}, b_{2}, \ldots, b_{n}$

$$
\begin{gathered}
\left(a_{1}^{2}+a_{2}^{2}+\ldots+a_{n}^{2}\right)\left(b_{1}^{2}+b_{2}^{2}+\ldots+b_{n}^{2}\right) \geq \\
\geq\left(a_{1} b_{1}+a_{2} b_{2}+\ldots+a_{n} b_{n}\right)^{2}
\end{gathered}
$$

with equality if and only if $a_{i}$ and $b_{i}$ are proportional, $i=1,2, \ldots, n$.

For any real numbers $a_{1}, a_{2}, \ldots, a_{n}$ and $b_{1}, b_{2}, \ldots, b_{n}$

$$
\begin{gathered}
\left(a_{1}^{2}+a_{2}^{2}+\ldots+a_{n}^{2}\right)\left(b_{1}^{2}+b_{2}^{2}+\ldots+b_{n}^{2}\right) \geq \\
\geq\left(a_{1} b_{1}+a_{2} b_{2}+\ldots+a_{n} b_{n}\right)^{2}
\end{gathered}
$$

with equality if and only if $a_{i}$ and $b_{i}$ are proportional, $i=1,2, \ldots, n$.

solution:
We'll show stronger inequality, i.e.
$$
\left(a^{2}+a b+b^{2}\right)\left(b^{2}+b c+c^{2}\right)\left(c^{2}+c a+a^{2}\right) \geq(a b+b c+c a)^{3}
$$

By Hlder's inequality we have
$$
\begin{aligned}
& \left(a^{2}+a b+b^{2}\right)\left(b^{2}+b c+c^{2}\right)\left(c^{2}+c a+a^{2}\right) \\
& \quad=\left(a b+a^{2}+b^{2}\right)\left(b^{2}+c^{2}+b c\right)\left(a^{2}+c a+c^{2}\right) \geq(a b+b c+c a)^{3}
\end{aligned}
$$
as required.

Without loss of generality we may assume that $a \leq b \leq c$. Then clearly $\alpha \leq \beta \leq \gamma, a+b \leq a+c \leq b+c$ and $\frac{1}{\gamma} \leq \frac{1}{\beta} \leq \frac{1}{\alpha}$.

Now by Chebishev's inequality we have
$$
\begin{aligned}
& ((a+b)+(b+c)+(c+a))\left(\frac{1}{\alpha}+\frac{1}{\beta}+\frac{1}{\gamma}\right) \\
& \quad \leq 3\left((b+c) \frac{1}{\alpha}+(c+a) \frac{1}{\beta}+(a+b) \frac{1}{\gamma}\right)
\end{aligned}
$$
i.e.
$$
\begin{equation*}
\frac{b+c}{\alpha}+\frac{c+a}{\beta}+\frac{a+b}{\gamma} \geq \frac{4 s}{3}\left(\frac{1}{\alpha}+\frac{1}{\beta}+\frac{1}{\gamma}\right) \tag{1}
\end{equation*}
$$

Using (1) and $A M \geq H M$ we obtain
$$
\frac{b+c}{\alpha}+\frac{c+a}{\beta}+\frac{a+b}{\gamma} \geq \frac{4 s}{3}\left(\frac{1}{\alpha}+\frac{1}{\beta}+\frac{1}{\gamma}\right) \geq \frac{4 s}{3} \cdot \frac{9}{\alpha+\beta+\gamma}=\frac{12 s}{\pi}
$$

Equality occurs iff $a=b=c$.

Theorem 40.Theorem:
Let $f:(a, b) \rightarrow \mathbb{R}$ be a convex function on the interval $(a, b)$. Let $n \in \mathbb{N}$ and $\alpha_{1}, \alpha_{2}, \ldots, \alpha_{n} \in(0,1)$ be real numbers such that $\alpha_{1}+\alpha_{2}+\cdots+\alpha_{n}=1$. Then for any $x_{1}, x_{2}, \ldots, x_{n} \in(a, b)$ we have
$$
f\left(\sum_{i=1}^{n} \alpha_{i} x_{i}\right) \leq \sum_{i=1}^{n} \alpha_{i} f\left(x_{i}\right)
$$
i.e.
$$
\begin{equation*}
f\left(\alpha_{1} x_{1}+\alpha_{2} x_{2}+\cdots+\alpha_{n} x_{n}\right) \leq \alpha_{1} f\left(x_{1}\right)+\alpha_{2} f\left(x_{2}\right)+\cdots+\alpha_{n} f\left(x_{n}\right) \tag{7.2}
\end{equation*}
$$

solution:
We have
$$
\begin{aligned}
\sqrt{\frac{a+b}{c}}+\sqrt{\frac{b+c}{a}}+\sqrt{\frac{c+a}{b}} & \stackrel{A \geq G}{\geq} 3 \sqrt[3]{\sqrt{\left(\frac{a+b}{c}\right)\left(\frac{b+c}{a}\right)\left(\frac{c+a}{b}\right)}} \\
& =3 \sqrt[6]{\frac{(a+b)(b+c)(c+a)}{a b c}} \\
& \stackrel{A \geq G}{\geq} \sqrt[6]{\frac{2^{3} \sqrt{a b} \cdot \sqrt{b c} \cdot \sqrt{c a}}{a b c}}=3 \sqrt{2}
\end{aligned}
$$

Equality occurs if and only if $a=b=c$.

Observe that
$$
\begin{equation*}
\frac{a^{2}}{b}+\frac{b^{2}}{c}+\frac{c^{2}}{a}=\frac{a^{2}-a b+b^{2}}{b}+\frac{b^{2}-b c+c^{2}}{c}+\frac{c^{2}-c a+a^{2}}{a} \tag{1}
\end{equation*}
$$

Since for any $x, y \in \mathbb{R}$, we have $x^{2}-x y+y^{2} \geq x y$, by (1) we get
$$
\frac{a^{2}}{b}+\frac{b^{2}}{c}+\frac{c^{2}}{a} \geq \frac{a b}{b}+\frac{b c}{c}+\frac{c a}{a}=a+b+c
$$

Since $a b c d=1$, there are two numbers $x, y$ among $a, b, c, d$, such that $x, y \geq 1$ or $x, y \leq 1$. Without loss of generality we may suppose that they are $b$ and $d$. Then clearly $(b-1)(d-1) \geq 0$, i.e. $b d+1 \geq b+d$.

According to the Cauchy-Schwarz inequality and the previous note, we obtain
$$
\begin{aligned}
\left(1+a^{2}\right)\left(1+b^{2}\right)\left(1+c^{2}\right)\left(1+d^{2}\right) & =\left(1+a^{2}+b^{2}+a^{2} b^{2}\right)\left(c^{2}+1+d^{2}+c^{2} d^{2}\right) \\
& \geq(c+a+b d+1)^{2} \geq(a+b+c+d)^{2}
\end{aligned}
$$

Equality holds iff $a=b=c=d=1$.

Applying the Cauchy-Schwarz inequality we get
$$
\begin{equation*}
a \sqrt{b+c}+b \sqrt{c+a}+c \sqrt{a+b} \leq \sqrt{2\left(a^{2}+b^{2}+c^{2}\right)(a+b+c)} \tag{1}
\end{equation*}
$$

Using Chebishev's inequality we get
$$
\begin{equation*}
\sqrt{2\left(a^{2}+b^{2}+c^{2}\right)(a+b+c)} \leq \sqrt{6\left(a^{3}+b^{3}+c^{3}\right)} \tag{2}
\end{equation*}
$$

Also from $A M \geq G M$ we have
$$
\begin{equation*}
a^{3}+b^{3}+c^{3} \geq 3 a b c=6 \tag{3}
\end{equation*}
$$

Combining (1), (2) and (3) we have
$$
a^{3}+b^{3}+c^{3} \geq \sqrt{6\left(a^{3}+b^{3}+c^{3}\right)} \geq a \sqrt{b+c}+b \sqrt{c+a}+c \sqrt{a+b}
$$

Equality holds iff $a=b=c=\sqrt[3]{2}$.

We have
$$
2 s=a+b+c \geq 3 \sqrt[3]{a b c}=3 \sqrt[3]{4 P R}=3 \sqrt[3]{4 s r R} \geq 3 \sqrt[3]{8 s r^{2}}
$$
i.e.
$$
s \geq 3 \sqrt[3]{s r^{2}}
$$
or
$$
s \geq 3 r \sqrt{3}
$$

Equality occurs if and only if $a=b=c$.2 We have
$$
\begin{equation*}
\frac{s}{3}=\frac{(s-a)+(s-b)+(s-c)}{3} \stackrel{A M \geq G M}{\geq} \sqrt[3]{(s-a)(s-b)(s-c)} \tag{1}
\end{equation*}
$$

Also
$$
\begin{equation*}
(s-a)(s-b)(s-c)=\frac{P^{2}}{s}=\frac{s^{2} r^{2}}{s}=s r^{2} \tag{2}
\end{equation*}
$$

By (1) and (2) we obtain
$$
s \geq 3 \sqrt[3]{s r^{2}}, \quad \text { i.e. } \quad s \geq 3 \sqrt{3} r
$$

Equality occurs if and only if $a=b=c$.

By the power mean inequality we have that
$$
\begin{aligned}
& M_{2}(a, b, c) \leq M_{3}(a, b, c) \\
& \quad \Leftrightarrow \quad \sqrt{\frac{a^{2}+b^{2}+c^{2}}{3}} \leq \sqrt[3]{\frac{a^{3}+b^{3}+c^{3}}{3}} \\
& \quad \Leftrightarrow \quad\left(a^{2}+b^{2}+c^{2}\right)^{3} \leq 3\left(a^{3}+b^{3}+c^{3}\right)^{2}
\end{aligned}
$$

For any real number $x$, the numbers $x-1, x^{2}-1, x^{3}-1$ and $x^{4}-1$, are of the same sign.

Therefore
$$
(x-1)\left(x^{3}-1\right) \geq 0, \quad\left(x^{2}-1\right)\left(x^{3}-1\right) \geq 0 \quad \text { and } \quad\left(x^{3}-1\right)\left(x^{4}-1\right) \geq 0
$$
i.e.
$$
\begin{array}{r}
c^{4}-c^{3}-c+1 \geq 0 \tag{1}
\end{array}
$$
$$
\begin{array}{r}
b^{5}-b^{3}-b^{2}+1 \geq 0 \tag{2}
\end{array}
$$
$$
\begin{array}{r}
a^{7}-a^{4}-a^{3}+1 \geq 0 \tag{3}
\end{array}
$$

By (1), (2) and (3) we have
$$
a^{7}-a^{4}+3 \geq a^{3}+2, \quad b^{5}-b^{2}+3 \geq b^{3}+2 \quad \text { and } \quad c^{4}-c+3 \geq c^{3}+2
$$

After multiplying these inequalities it follows that
$$
\begin{equation*}
\left(a^{7}-a^{4}+3\right)\left(b^{5}-b^{2}+3\right)\left(c^{4}-c+3\right) \geq\left(a^{3}+2\right)\left(b^{3}+2\right)\left(c^{3}+2\right) \tag{4}
\end{equation*}
$$

Analogously as in Problem 126, we can prove that
$$
\begin{equation*}
\left(a^{3}+2\right)\left(b^{3}+2\right)\left(c^{3}+2\right) \geq(a+b+c)^{3} \tag{5}
\end{equation*}
$$

By the obvious inequality $(a+b+c)^{2} \geq 3(a b+b c+c a)$, since $a b+b c+c a=3$ we deduce that
$$
\begin{equation*}
a+b+c \geq 3 \tag{6}
\end{equation*}
$$

Finally from (4), (5) and (6) we obtain the required inequality.
Equality occurs iff $a=b=c=1$.

Theorem 43.Theorem:
Let $a_{i} \in(0, \infty), i=1,2, \ldots, n$, and $\alpha_{i} \in[0,1], i=1,2, \ldots, n$, be such that $\alpha_{1}+\alpha_{2}+\cdots+\alpha_{n}=1$.
Then
