Theorem 40.Theorem:
Let $f:(a, b) \rightarrow \mathbb{R}$ be a convex function on the interval $(a, b)$. Let $n \in \mathbb{N}$ and $\alpha_{1}, \alpha_{2}, \ldots, \alpha_{n} \in(0,1)$ be real numbers such that $\alpha_{1}+\alpha_{2}+\cdots+\alpha_{n}=1$. Then for any $x_{1}, x_{2}, \ldots, x_{n} \in(a, b)$ we have
$$
f\left(\sum_{i=1}^{n} \alpha_{i} x_{i}\right) \leq \sum_{i=1}^{n} \alpha_{i} f\left(x_{i}\right)
$$
i.e.
$$
\begin{equation*}
f\left(\alpha_{1} x_{1}+\alpha_{2} x_{2}+\cdots+\alpha_{n} x_{n}\right) \leq \alpha_{1} f\left(x_{1}\right)+\alpha_{2} f\left(x_{2}\right)+\cdots+\alpha_{n} f\left(x_{n}\right) \tag{7.2}
\end{equation*}
$$

solution:
Let $p=a+b+c, q=a b+b c+c a, r=a b c$.

Since $\frac{1}{a+1}+\frac{1}{b+1}+\frac{1}{c+1}=2$ we have
$$
\begin{equation*}
(a+1)(b+1)+(b+1)(c+1)+(c+1)(a+1)=2(a+1)(b+1)(c+1) \tag{1}
\end{equation*}
$$

Using the identities $I_{9}$ and $I_{10}$, identity (1) becomes $3+2 p+q=2(1+p+$ $q+r$ ), from which it follows that
$$
\begin{equation*}
q+2 r=1 \tag{2}
\end{equation*}
$$

It can easily be shown that
$(8 a b+1)(8 b c+1)+(8 b c+1)(8 c a+1)+(8 c a+1)(8 a b+1)=64 p r+16 q+3$ and
$$
(8 a b+1)(8 b c+1)(8 c a+1)=512 r^{2}+64 p r+8 q+1
$$

We need to prove that
$$
64 p r+16 q+3 \geq 512 r^{2}+64 p r+8 q+1
$$
which is equivalent to
$$
\begin{equation*}
8 q+2 \geq 512 r^{2} \tag{3}
\end{equation*}
$$

By $q^{3} \geq 27 r^{2}$ and since $q=1-2 r$ we obtain
$$
\begin{aligned}
& (1-2 r)^{3} \geq 27 r^{2} \\
& \quad \Leftrightarrow \quad 8 r^{3}+15 r^{2}+6 r-1 \leq 0 \\
& \quad \Leftrightarrow \quad(8 r-1)\left(r^{2}+2 r+1\right) \leq 0
\end{aligned}
$$

Thus
$$
\begin{equation*}
8 r-1 \leq 0, \quad \text { i.e. } \quad r \leq \frac{1}{8} \tag{4}
\end{equation*}
$$

Now since $q+2 r=1$, inequality (3) becomes
$$
\begin{aligned}
& 8(1-2 r)+2 \geq 512 r^{2} \\
& \quad \Leftrightarrow \quad 512 r^{2}+16 r-10 \leq 0 \\
& \quad \Leftrightarrow \quad(8 r-1)(64 r+10) \leq 0
\end{aligned}
$$
which follows due to (4).

Theorem 5.Theorem:
For any real numbers $a_{1}, a_{2}, \ldots, a_{n}$ and $b_{1}, b_{2}, \ldots, b_{n}$

$$
\begin{gathered}
\left(a_{1}^{2}+a_{2}^{2}+\ldots+a_{n}^{2}\right)\left(b_{1}^{2}+b_{2}^{2}+\ldots+b_{n}^{2}\right) \geq \\
\geq\left(a_{1} b_{1}+a_{2} b_{2}+\ldots+a_{n} b_{n}\right)^{2}
\end{gathered}
$$

with equality if and only if $a_{i}$ and $b_{i}$ are proportional, $i=1,2, \ldots, n$.

solution:
The given inequality is equivalent to
$$
\begin{aligned}
& \frac{1}{8 a b c}-\frac{1}{8 a b c+(a+b-c)^{3}}+\frac{1}{8 a b c}-\frac{1}{8 a b c+(b+c-a)^{3}}+\frac{1}{8 a b c} \\
& \quad-\frac{1}{8 a b c+(c+a-b)^{3}} \\
& \quad \geq \frac{3}{8 a b c}-\frac{1}{3 a b c}
