Theorem 36.Theorem:
Let $a_{1} \leq a_{2} \leq \cdots \leq a_{n}$ and $b_{1} \leq$ $b_{2} \leq \cdots \leq b_{n}$ be real numbers. For any permutation $\left(x_{1}, x_{2}, \ldots, x_{n}\right)$ of $\left(a_{1}, a_{2}, \ldots, a_{n}\right)$ we have the following inequalities:
$$
\begin{aligned}
a_{1} b_{1}+a_{2} b_{2}+\cdots+a_{n} b_{n} & \geq x_{1} b_{1}+x_{2} b_{2}+\cdots+x_{n} b_{n} \\
& \geq a_{n} b_{1}+a_{n-1} b_{2}+\cdots+a_{1} b_{n}
\end{aligned}
$$

solution:
We have
$$
\begin{equation*}
(a+b+c)^{2} \geq 3(a b+b c+c a)=\frac{3 a b c}{2 P}\left(h_{a}+h_{b}+h_{c}\right)=6 R \cdot\left(h_{a}+h_{b}+h_{c}\right) \tag{1}
\end{equation*}
$$

Recall the well-known inequality $a^{2}+b^{2}+c^{2} \leq 9 R^{2}$.
Then we have
$$
\begin{equation*}
(a+b+c)^{2} \leq 3\left(a^{2}+b^{2}+c^{2}\right) \leq 27 R^{2}, \text { i.e. } \quad a+b+c \leq 3 \sqrt{3} R \tag{2}
\end{equation*}
$$

Now by (1) and (2) we get
$$
